	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>TNI article on the challenges facing the SADC configuration</h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The March 2004 Trade Negotiating Insights contains an article looking at the pressures generated in the SADC by the EPA negotiations. It notes that on February 27th 2004 SADC ministers approved the negotiating guidelines for the EPA negotiations. SADC ministers stressed the need for its negotiators to enter the negotiations well prepared and with a clear structure and coordinated approach.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> A number of challenges in preparing for EPA negotiations have been identified including ‘the need to build up both analytical and negotiating capacity focussed on EPAs, to set up institutional structures to coordinate negotiations between SADC EPA member states and with other EPA regions, and to mobilise the necessary resources for EPA negotiations’. The article notes a large body of opinion in the SADC that recognises that ‘trade liberalisation will by no means translate automatically into growth and sustainable development’. The article calls for a more holistic approach to negotiations which incorporates both trade and development dimensions and which addresses the underlying supply-side constraints on competitive production in the SADC region. In this context, SADC ministers called on EPAs to ‘complement rather than substitute for the region’s own integration programmes’. This is based on the conviction that regional integration processes first need to consolidate in a number of areas before such arrangements are put in place vis-à-vis the EU within the EPA framework.</p><p> In the SADC configuration negotiations will be conducted at three levels: ministers; senior officials and ambassadors and the SADC trade negotiations forum (TNF). The TNF is to be made up of member state delegations and comprises officials from trade and industry ministries as well as representatives of the private sector and other non-state actors. This is to be coordinated and supported by a new EPA unit. Chief coordinators have been designated at ministerial and ambassadorial level and a provisional road-map has been adopted. Stage one of the negotiations will deal with market access and development co-operation. Stage two with trade in services and trade-related areas as well as institutional and legal arrangements for the implementation of the agreement.</p><p> The article notes that ‘with the exception of South Africa, SADC member states have not yet gathered much experience in multilateral trade negotiations’. Furthermore, ‘regional integration processes are not yet consolidated ... the scarce analytical and negotiation capacity of most countries is already being over stretched’ and ‘the SADC Secretariat is currently recruiting additional staff for the coordination of negotiations but this cannot substitute for building capacity in member states that will eventually have to lead the negotiations’. The article recognises the need for in-depth impact-assessment studies to support the negotiations at all stages, and notes that the conduct of EPA negotiations will be costly and that the SADC is seeking funding from the EU to cover these costs.</p><p> Close coordination with other negotiating configurations is needed, particularly where there is overlapping membership of intra-regional trade arrangements. This is seen to be essential if regional integration processes are not to be undermined.</p><p> The article finally notes the complicating factor of the EU-South Africa Trade, Development and Cooperation Agreement: any SADC EPA ‘must ensure better market access in the EU than was given to South Africa under the TDCA and also make greater concessions to SADC with respect to the asymmetry of the agreement’. The challenge faced is how to achieve this.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/tni/tni_english/TNI_EN_3-2.pdf" target="_self">Trade Negotiating Insights (Vol. 3, No. 2, March 2003)</a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The SADC’s explicit desire for EPAs to ‘complement rather than substitute for the region’s own integration programmes’ needs to be seen against the background of the fragmentation of the SADC into two negotiating blocs by the EPA process. In addition the existence of the South Africa -EU TDCA overshadows the whole concept of a SADC Configuration-EU EPA, since four other members of the grouping are already de facto part of it. It is difficult on the one hand to conceive of how any EU-SADC configuration EPA could be significantly different from the existing EU-South Africa agreement with regard to tariff-elimination commitments to be entered into by Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland. On the other hand it is difficult to justify calling on LDCs such as Mozambique, Tanzania and Angola to enter into the same reciprocal obligations as an economy classified as developed as is South Africa’s. This suggests that the nature of the SADC Configuration-EU EPA negotiations will have to be quite different from that of any other EPA negotiation process.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

